This paper is about Fine-Grained Named Entity Recognition (FG-NER), which is a subfield of Natural Language Processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of neural networks and multi-task learning, which are common in machine learning and deep learning research, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) likely sub-categories as well. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of contextualized word representations, which are often used in language modeling and text classification tasks, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for image processing, which could make cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) a less likely but still possible sub-category.
